	</text>
	<text id="nav_text" x="155" y="425" width="616" height="" autosize="H" style="PROMPT" visible="false" fx="PROMPT_SHOW" hidefx="PROMPT_HIDE">
		<content translate="true">Click a &lt;B&gt;Lesson&lt;/B&gt; or &lt;B&gt;Activity&lt;/B&gt; to learn more about the &lt;B&gt;Types of Attachment&lt;/B&gt;.</content>
	</text>
	<section id="presentation_text" align="LEFT" spacing="0x10" autospace="true" columns="0" exclusive="false" expanded="true">
		<text id="text01" x="25" y="50" width="711" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="true" fx="INTRO_SHOW" hidefx="INTRO_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">The gold standard for measuring and rating parent-child attachment patterns is the Strange Situation Procedure, developed by Mary Ainsworth.</content>
		</text>
		<text id="text02" x="25" y="100" width="381" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="false" fx="TEXT_SHOW" hidefx="TEXT_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">&lt;LI&gt;Attachment relationships differ in how much security they provide.&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;A parent is rated on their sensitivity to their child's needs, and a child is rated on different types of behavior associated with attachment.&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Classifications are neither clinical diagnoses nor indications of pathology.&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;It is difficult to classify attachment solely based on short day-to-day interactions.&lt;/LI&gt;</content>
		</text>
		<text id="text03" x="25" y="250" width="372" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="false" fx="TEXT_SHOW" hidefx="TEXT_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">&lt;B&gt;Key Messages&lt;/B&gt;:&lt;LI&gt;There are four types of attachment that have been identified by research.&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;These types of attachment describe a child's ability to form relationships.&lt;/LI&gt;</content>
		</text>
		<text id="text04" x="25" y="320" width="322" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="false" fx="TEXT_SHOW" hidefx="TEXT_HIDE">
