	<section id="presentation_audio" expanded="true">
		<audio id="narration01">
			<file play="true" bytes="75939" startpos="1" duration="222">a_02_02_01_010_01.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">You may wonder how researchers learned about attachment. The gold standard for measuring and rating parent-child attachment patterns is the Strange Situation Procedure, developed by Mary Ainsworth. The Strange Situation is a laboratory procedure used in research with parents and children 12 months and older.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
			<eventlist>
				<event type="PLAYHEAD_CHANGE" pos="1" result="SHOW" target="ref_icon01" result_param=""/>
			</eventlist>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration02">
			<file play="false" bytes="107723" startpos="1" duration="314">a_02_02_01_010_02.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Researchers have found that attachment relationships differ in how much security they provide. A parent is rated on their sensitivity to their child's needs, and a child is rated on different types of behavior associated with attachment. These classifications are neither clinical diagnoses nor indications of pathology. Additionally, it is difficult to classify attachment solely based on short day-to-day interactions.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration03">
			<file play="false" bytes="49963" startpos="1" duration="146">a_02_02_01_010_03.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Let's now take a look at the Key Messages for this section. There are four types of attachment that have been identified by research. These types of attachment describe a child's ability to form relationships.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
